otAllocator allocator = new RootAllocator(1024)) {\\n            assertThat(allocator.getLimit()).isEqualTo(1024);\\n            assertThat(allocator.getAllocatedMemory()).isZero();\\n        } finally {\\n            restoreAllocationManagerType(previousAllocationManagerType);\\n        }\\n    }\\n\\n    private static void restoreAllocationManagerType(String previousAllocationManagerType) {\\n        if (previousAllocationManagerType == null) {\\n            System.clearProperty(DefaultAllocationManagerOption.ALLOCATION_MANAGER_TYPE_PROPERTY_NAME);\\n        } else {\\n            System.setProperty(\\n                    DefaultAllocationManagerOption.ALLOCATION_MANAGER_TYPE_PROPERTY_NAME,\\n                    previousAllocationManagerType);\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777796708554}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.arrow:arrow-memory-core:7.0.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T08-25-38-332902Z.log:2668:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering dependency changes**\\n\\nI'm thinking about maybe adding some dependency changes and ensuring that each dynamic-access class has its own dedicated Java test file. Right now, we only have DefaultAllocationManagerOptionTest, which is an improvement since I removed a broad placeholder. I also need to check if all top-level test classes should be public, as we only have one public class. Additionally, there's a potential issue regarding reflection and native image execution. I'll need to consider these points more closely as I move forward.\\n\\n**Examining constant inlining**\\n\\nI’m wondering if the compiler will inline constants from an external JAR. The variable is declared as a public static final String literal, so typically, javac should inline it. But, if it doesn't, could accessing that constant end up initializing the class? The Java Language Specification (J